adiated homes. Their determination to recover their land, cultures, and histories for future generations provides a compelling case study for reimagining relationality and accountability in the ever-atomizing world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFukushima Nuclear Disaster, Japan, 2011. 0aRadioactive pollutionzJapanzFukushima-ken. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2023 Englishz978311131910008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2023z9783111318141oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520394124?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520394124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520394124/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131910-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-SEWb2023